"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:11.3.1.9\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">11.3.1.9</span> Bath</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">בַּת</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(bath)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs7:26\">1KI 7:26</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs7:38\">1KI 7:38</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr2:9\">2CH 2:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr2:9\">2CH 2:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr4:5\">2CH 4:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa5:10\">ISA 5:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:10\">EZK 45:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:11\">EZK 45:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:11\">EZK 45:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:14\">EZK 45:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:14\">EZK 45:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:14\">EZK 45:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:14\">EZK 45:14</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">The <em>bath</em> is the liquid equivalent to the <em>’eyfah</em> dry measure.</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs7:26\">1KI 7:26</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr4:5\">2CH 4:5</a>: In these verses the capacity of the bronze Sea is given according to the <em>bath</em> measure. Since scholars do not agree on the size of the <em>bath</em>, translations differ wildly on the capacity of the bronze Sea in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs7:26\">1KI 7:26</a>: 80,000 liters (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"French Common Language Version (Bible en français courant)\">FRCL</abbr>), 40,000 liters (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"German Common Language Version (Gute Nachricht Bibel)\">GECL</abbr>), 11,000 gallons (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr>), 10,000 gallons (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>), and so. It is to be noted that <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs7:26\">1KI 7:26</a> gives the capacity as 2,000 baths, while <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr4:5\">2CH 4:5</a> has 3,000 baths. Translators should not try to harmonize these figures. See also the discussion under <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">4.3.2 Temple: Sea, tank&lt;REALIA:4.3.2&gt;</a>.</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa5:10\">ISA 5:10</a>: See the comments under <em>chomer</em> above, <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">11.3.1.4 Homer&lt;REALIA:11.3.1.4&gt;</a>.</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:10\">EZK 45:10</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:11\">EZK 45:11</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:11\">EZK 45:11</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:14\">EZK 45:14</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:14\">EZK 45:14</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:14\">EZK 45:14</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:14\">EZK 45:14</a>: This passage equates the ephah and the bath. They are both one-tenth of a homer.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
